CHAPTER XXXIX.

OF POLISHING THE GILDING.

TAKE fine brass wire, bending it so that the folds may be the length of a finger; and when they have been four times folded, bind them with a flaxen thread so that they may be as one. Of these parcels make four, or five, or six, so that one kind may have three, another four, a third five, and so increasing unto eight. All these being separately tied up, make a small hole in a piece of wood, in which you place one of these small bundles, and pour in lead, so that when it has become cold, and you have taken it out, these folds may adhere together as if fixed in a leaden knob. In this manner make with each parcel separate leaden knobs, and now cutting all the ligatures at the other end, file and serape their tops, that they may become round and smooth; when with these, as if carving them, you have polished them, you polish the gilt handles in pure water and in a clean vessel.
